Since $2x+7$ is a factor, we should get a remainder of $0$ when we divide $6x^3+19x^2+cx+35$.
\[
\begin{array}{c|cccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{3x^2} & -x&+5  \\
\cline{2-5}
2x+7 & 6x^3&+19x^2&+cx&+35 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-6x^3} & -21x^2  \\ 
\cline{2-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & -2x^2 & +cx  \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & +2x^2 & +7x \\ 
\cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & (c+7)x & + 35 \\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & -10x & -35 \\ 
\cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & (c+7-10)x & 0 \\ 
\end{array}
\]The remainder is $0$ if $c+7-10=0$, so $c=\boxed{3}$.

The prime factorization of $432 = 2^4 \cdot 3^3$. It follows that the sum of the divisors is equal to $(1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + 2^4)(1 + 3 + 3^2 + 3^3)$, as each factor of $432$ is represented when the product is expanded. We have to subtract $432$ so that we only count the proper divisors, so the answer is \begin{align*}
(1 + 2 + 4 + 8 + 16)(1 + 3 + 9 + 27) - 432 &= (31)(40) - 432\\
&= 1240 - 432\\
&= \boxed{808}.\\
\end{align*}
